The paper proposes a technique for matching image pairs that are significantly disparate in nature, which is a common problem in computer vision. The proposed technique uses local feature descriptors to derive a complex high-level global shape representation for matching disparate images, which suggests that it belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of a saliency-based component for tackling noisy correspondences arising from the presence of textureless regions and complex backgrounds, which suggests that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of eigenspectral decomposition for reasoning about shape similarity, which suggests that it may belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also involves constructing a joint image graph and computing distances between interest points, which suggests that it may belong to the graphics (cs.GR) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a technique for matching image pairs, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
